---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import Alert from '../../components/Alert.astro';
import Accordion from '../../components/Accordion.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="Troubleshooting: Child Bypassed Filter"
	description="Discovered your child found a way around filtering. Learn common bypass methods and how to strengthen protection while rebuilding trust."
>
	<Breadcrumb />

	<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
		<header class="relative pb-6 border-b-[3px] border-blue-600 dark:border-blue-500 mb-8">
			<div class="inline-block px-4 py-2 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold mb-4 bg-red-100 dark:bg-red-900 text-red-800 dark:text-red-100">Advanced</div>
			<h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3 leading-tight">Child Bypassed Filter</h1>
			<p class="text-xl text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
				Discovered your child found a way around filtering. Close common bypass methods and strengthen protection.
			</p>
			<div class="flex gap-6 flex-wrap text-base text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
				<span>‚è±Ô∏è Time Required: 30-60 minutes</span>
				<span>üîß Difficulty: Advanced</span>
			</div>
		</header>

		<Alert type="error">
			<strong>First Priority: Have a conversation.</strong> Technical fixes matter less than addressing the motivation
			and rebuilding trust. Punitive measures alone often backfire.
		</Alert>

		<section class="mt-10">
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">Step 1: Assess the Situation Calmly</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Before reacting, gather information:</p>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Questions to Answer:</h3>
			<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>How did they bypass?</strong> (Device setting? App? Website?)</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>What were they accessing?</strong> (Blocked games? Social media? Inappropriate content?)</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>How long has this been happening?</strong> (One time? Weeks?)</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Did they know it was wrong?</strong> (Deliberate deception vs. exploring technology?)</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Why did they do it?</strong> (Curiosity? Peer pressure? Addiction? Research legitimate need?)</li>
			</ul>

			<div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4 my-4 rounded">
				<strong class="block text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-100 mb-2">Important Context:</strong>
				<p class="text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-100 mb-0">
					Tech-savvy kids bypassing filters is common. It doesn't mean you're a bad parent or they're a bad kid.
					It's an opportunity for growth and improved communication.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="mt-10">
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">Step 2: Close the Bypass Method</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Identify how they bypassed filtering and close that loophole:</p>

			<div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mt-6">
				<Accordion title="Method 1: VPN Apps" defaultOpen={true}>
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">VPN apps encrypt all traffic and route it through external servers, bypassing DNS filtering entirely.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">Signs of Use:</h4>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">VPN icon in device status bar</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Apps like NordVPN, ExpressVPN, free VPNs (Turbo VPN, Thunder VPN)</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Browser extensions (Hola, Touch VPN)</li>
					</ul>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Block:</h4>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">iOS:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Settings ‚Üí Screen Time ‚Üí Content & Privacy Restrictions ‚Üí Enable</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Allowed Apps ‚Üí Turn OFF "VPN & Device Management"</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Removes ability to install/use VPN profiles</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Check: Settings ‚Üí General ‚Üí VPN & Device Management (should be unavailable)</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Android:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Family Link app (parent device)</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Select child ‚Üí Manage settings ‚Üí Apps on Google Play</li>
						<li class="mb-2">All apps require approval ‚Üí Enable</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Manually uninstall existing VPN apps</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Alternatively: Settings ‚Üí Apps ‚Üí VPN app ‚Üí Force stop ‚Üí Disable</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Windows:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Microsoft Family Safety online dashboard</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Select child ‚Üí Apps and games</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Block specific VPN applications</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Or: Use AppLocker (Windows Pro) to block VPN executables</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Mac:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Screen Time ‚Üí App Limits</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Block VPN apps individually</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Or: System Settings ‚Üí Users & Groups ‚Üí Remove admin rights (prevents VPN installation)</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Router-Level (Best):</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Router admin ‚Üí Firewall or Security</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Block VPN ports: 1194 (OpenVPN), 500/4500 (IPSec), 1723 (PPTP)</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Block VPN protocols if router supports it</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Use DNS filtering that includes VPN category blocking</li>
					</ol>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 2: DNS Server Changes">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Manually changing device DNS settings to 8.8.8.8 (Google) or 1.1.1.1 (Cloudflare) bypasses filtering DNS.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Block:</h4>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Router-Level (Recommended):</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Most consumer routers can't force DNS, but some can</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Look for "DNS Relay," "DNS Proxy," or "Force DNS" option</li>
						<li class="mb-2">ASUS AiProtection: Automatically forces router DNS</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Advanced routers (pfSense): Use firewall rules to redirect all port 53 traffic</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Device-Level:</strong>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>iOS:</strong> Configure DNS as "supervised device" (requires Apple Configurator)</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Android:</strong> Family Link doesn't prevent DNS changes - requires supervision</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Windows:</strong> Family Safety doesn't lock DNS - requires admin restrictions</li>
					</ul>

					<Alert type="warning">
						Consumer-level tools struggle to prevent DNS changes. Layer additional protections (device controls,
						monitoring software).
					</Alert>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 3: Using Mobile Data Instead of WiFi">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Turning off WiFi and using cellular data bypasses home network filtering.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Block:</h4>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">iOS:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Screen Time ‚Üí Content & Privacy Restrictions</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Allow Changes ‚Üí Cellular Data Changes ‚Üí Don't Allow</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Prevents disabling WiFi or enabling cellular data</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Android:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Family Link ‚Üí Manage settings ‚Üí Controls on Google Play</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Require approval for all apps</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Note: Can't directly prevent WiFi/data toggling</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Alternative: Don't provide a phone with data plan</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Carrier-Level Filtering:</strong>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Verizon Smart Family: $5/month, filters cellular data</li>
						<li class="mb-2">AT&T Secure Family: $7.99/month, filters cellular data</li>
						<li class="mb-2">T-Mobile FamilyMode: $10/month, filters cellular data</li>
					</ul>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 4: Proxy Websites">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Websites like HideMyAss, ProxySite, CroxyProxy act as intermediaries to access blocked sites.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Block:</h4>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Most filtering DNS providers block known proxy sites</li>
						<li class="mb-2">If using OpenDNS: Block "Proxy/Anonymizer" category</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Check block logs to see which proxies were accessed, add to blocklist</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Enable SafeSearch (prevents finding new proxy sites via Google)</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Monitor software (Bark, Qustodio) alerts to proxy usage</li>
					</ul>

					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">
						<strong>Challenge:</strong> New proxy sites appear daily. DNS filtering + monitoring is most effective.
					</p>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 5: Using Another Device">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Using parent's laptop, sibling's tablet, or friend's phone to access content.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Prevent:</h4>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Physical security:</strong> Lock your devices, don't share passwords</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Filter all devices:</strong> Apply filtering to every device in home</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Guest network:</strong> Put visitor devices on separate filtered WiFi</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Account-level controls:</strong> Use Google SafeSearch enforcement, YouTube Restricted Mode locked to account</li>
					</ul>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 6: Resetting Device to Factory Settings">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Factory reset removes parental controls, filtering apps, and restrictions.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Block:</h4>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">iOS:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Screen Time ‚Üí Content & Privacy Restrictions</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Allow Changes ‚Üí Account Changes ‚Üí Don't Allow</li>
						<li class="mb-2">This prevents signing out of iCloud (necessary for reset)</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Android:</strong>
					<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Family Link automatically prevents factory reset</li>
						<li class="mb-2">Requires parent approval code to reset</li>
					</ol>

					<strong class="text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200">Computers:</strong>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2">Remove admin rights (prevents system changes)</li>
						<li class="mb-2">BIOS password (prevents booting from USB to bypass OS)</li>
					</ul>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 7: Browser Incognito/Private Mode">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Private browsing doesn't actually bypass filtering, but hides browser history from parents.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">Clarification:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">
						Incognito mode does NOT bypass DNS filtering or parental controls. It only prevents local history storage.
						If they're accessing blocked content in Incognito, another bypass method is in play.
					</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Block (If Desired):</h4>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>iOS:</strong> Screen Time ‚Üí Content & Privacy ‚Üí Allowed Apps ‚Üí Safari ‚Üí Disable (use only managed browser)</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Android:</strong> Family Link ‚Üí Chrome settings ‚Üí Disable Incognito</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Use monitoring software that captures activity regardless of Incognito</li>
					</ul>
				</Accordion>

				<Accordion title="Method 8: Using Someone Else's WiFi">
					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How It Works:</h4>
					<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Connecting to neighbor's WiFi, public WiFi, or friend's hotspot to avoid home filtering.</p>

					<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">How to Prevent:</h4>
					<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Device-level controls:</strong> iOS Screen Time and Android Family Link work on any network</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Filtering apps:</strong> Qustodio, Net Nanny, Bark filter on all connections</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>DNS profiles:</strong> NextDNS or CleanBrowsing VPN profiles filter on any WiFi</li>
						<li class="mb-2"><strong>Physical supervision:</strong> Devices stay in common areas, not bedrooms</li>
					</ul>

					<Alert type="info">
						This is why device-level controls are essential supplements to network filtering.
					</Alert>
				</Accordion>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="mt-10">
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">Step 3: Strengthen Your Overall Protection</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">One bypass reveals weaknesses. Implement layered protection:</p>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Layer 1: Network-Level (DNS)</h3>
			<ul class="list-none ml-0 space-y-2 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Use filtering DNS (OpenDNS, CleanBrowsing, Cloudflare Family)</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Set on router, not just devices</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Enable router firewall if available</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Block VPN ports at router level</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Layer 2: Device-Level (Built-in Controls)</h3>
			<ul class="list-none ml-0 space-y-2 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">iOS Screen Time configured correctly</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Android Family Link managed from parent device</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Windows Family Safety enabled</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">macOS Screen Time active</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Remove admin rights on computers</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Layer 3: Software Monitoring (Optional but Recommended)</h3>
			<ul class="list-none ml-0 space-y-2 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Qustodio, Net Nanny, or Bark on key devices</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Provides bypass attempt alerts</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Works on any network</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Can detect VPN usage</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Layer 4: Physical/Behavioral Controls</h3>
			<ul class="list-none ml-0 space-y-2 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Devices charge in parent's room overnight</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Screen time limits enforced</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Devices used in common areas</li>
				<li class="pl-6 relative before:content-['‚úì'] before:absolute before:left-0 before:text-green-600 dark:before:text-green-400 before:font-bold">Random spot-checks acceptable in family culture</li>
			</ul>

			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">
				<strong>Key Principle:</strong> If one layer fails, others catch the bypass. No single solution is perfect.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="mt-10">
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">Step 4: Have the Conversation</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Technology alone won't solve this. Communication is essential:</p>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Goals of the Conversation:</h3>
			<ol class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Understand motivations:</strong> Why did they bypass?</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Address root cause:</strong> Legitimate need? Addiction? Peer pressure?</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Rebuild trust:</strong> Acknowledge breach while maintaining relationship</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Set clear expectations:</strong> Rules about technology use</li>
				<li class="mb-2"><strong>Collaborative problem-solving:</strong> Can some restrictions be adjusted?</li>
			</ol>

			<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">Conversation Framework:</h3>

			<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">1. Start Calm and Curious (Not Accusatory):</h4>
			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3"><em>"I noticed you've been able to access [X]. Can you help me understand how that happened?"</em></p>

			<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">2. Listen First:</h4>
			<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="mb-2">Let them explain without interrupting</li>
				<li class="mb-2">Ask open-ended questions</li>
				<li class="mb-2">Try to understand their perspective</li>
			</ul>

			<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">3. Acknowledge Valid Concerns:</h4>
			<p class="leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">
				<em>"I hear that you felt the blocking was too strict. Let's talk about what's reasonable."</em>
			</p>

			<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">4. Explain Your Reasoning:</h4>
			<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="mb-2">Why filtering exists (protection, not control)</li>
				<li class="mb-2">Dangers you're trying to prevent (age-appropriate detail)</li>
				<li class="mb-2">Difference between trust and wisdom (trust them, don't trust the internet)</li>
			</ul>

			<h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mt-4 mb-3">5. Address Consequences:</h4>
			<ul class="ml-6 mb-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
				<li class="mb-2">Natural consequences (restored trust takes time)</li>
				<li class="mb-2">Logical consequences (stricter monitoring temporarily)</li>
